Eating better beef doesn’t mean you fancy. It means you like tastier and more nutritious beef which will enrich the lives of the people you love. @cartercountrymeats is that place. Yes it’s more expensive than most other places but your return on your investment is much greater than your initial purchase. I fed these ribeyes to a few of my buddies at the duck camp and they swore that I used butter to cook these steaks. They are perfectly marbled, incredibly juicy, and buttery to the point where you actually taste that flavor. Not only is this the tastiest beef I’ve ever had but they have science proving how nutrient dense and rich this beef actually is. (The key is the soil from the grass in which these cattle graze) In this video I get the lion share of the steak but Pman helps himself to a slice and handful of buttery fat from the rib cap. If y’all are looking for a great gift for the carnivore in your family then a box from @cartercountrymeats might be the way to go.  #usabeef #beef #steak #ribeye #dinner #carnivore #christmasgiftforhim #christmasgifts

The year of the rifle. The truth is that I gave up my .22 rifle when I was 12 years old for a 20 gauge youth model shotgun and I never looked back. This past year I purchased my first rifle, a Henry 308; which I’ve yet to make a hunt with. Next weekend, I’ll be heading to west Texas to hunt a low fence elk herd, and I knew that a reliable bolt rifle would give me a better opportunity for success. This will be my first elk hunt so I called on family members to give me a crash course with a firearm that could knock down an elk from 300-500 yards. Yesterday @stephenmcgee07 and I spent a few hours on the range getting accustomed to shooting his rifle at targets ranging from 100-850 yards. This rig is an absolute laser. I never knew that I dialed rifle could be that precise down range at that distance. I’m not afraid to admit that I know very little about big game hunting mostly because I’ve never done much of it. I’m a waterfowler and through the years I’ve always put most of my energy into chasing ducks and geese in the fall and winter. This year will be different starting with next weekend. Don’t get me wrong, I’ll always be a duck hunter, but in this year of the rifle, I plan on learning more about hunting game with muzzleloaders, lever actions, and bolt guns like this one in this image. Swipe left, and you’ll see (hear) the shot from 850 yards. Wish me luck!
#hunter #texas #freedom

How you make a gumbo is more important than the gumbo recipe. Notice, I did not add any seasoning (except salt and pepper ) which didn’t make the cut for the video. The reason I don’t need any seasoning is because I use GREAT andouille sausage. Ingredients matter and the sausage I use acts as the primary seasoning for my gumbo. Lucky for you @bourgeoismeatmarket ships so you can now make gumbo that taste as good as mine. Seriously folks, stop putting worsteshire and rotel in your gumbo. Make a dark rough, make good stock, and have great sausage. That’s the money maker. If you want a detailed recipe, just go to @meateater website and search for my coot gumbo. That recipe works for all kind of game meat. #fueledbynature #meateater #gumbo #duckrecipe #cajuncooking #cajunfood #southerncooikng #reels #recipe

Aa a #TeamBronco_Ambassador @ford has asked me to share my #BuiltFordProud story. Being able to live off the land and providing food for my family that is clean, organic and I know exactly where it came from is incredibly important to me. This is a tradition that was passed down to me through generations and I can’t wait to share this way of life with my son. However, continuing our way of life isn’t easy. According to the U.S. Geological Survey, the State of Louisiana is losing approximately one football field of land every hour to rising water levels. As hunters and conservationists, we are writing our own history and it is up to us to write a history that will make our sons and daughters proud. #ad @fordbronco

It might be my birthday today but as a new dad and freshly turning 39 I’ve reflected on those gifts that happen throughout the day. Whether small or big I believe it’s important to recognize the blessings and “gifts” that we receive daily. By far, the best birthday gift I could ever dream of is to wake up next to Candace everyday. I personally get caught up in the business of life way to often and while I’m out making moves away from home; she is the one making sure that the whole machine doesn’t crumble to the ground. At the same time, she has the unique ability to ground me in this place whenever I get home and cherish those everyday moments. That is a gift that can’t be bought or exchanged but hopefully once in your lifetime we can all experience. Although I deeply appreciate her, this is not an appreciation post. This is a Happy Birthday post to myself. Candace and her light is my everlasting gift, that no one can buy, that never will be exchanged, and I’ll forever cherish all of my days. I’m not an easy person to buy gifts for and that’s because in her, in God, and in our son; I have everything I could ever ask for. #birthdaypost #thankful #onemoretime #wife #family #birthday #love #blessed

Many of you have commented and messaged me about my own comment on the @bassproshops account featuring an onion, pepper, and cream cheese stuffed venison back strap which was then wrapped in bacon, smoked, and severely overcooked. It’s preposterous to know how hard hunters and anglers work to harvest game and fish and for some reason still seem stuck in this antiquated cooking history surrounding wild game. The days of “everything is better with bacon” and “got to remove the gaminess” are over. And it’s actually much simpler then you  think! BPS, when you are ready to talk about wild game cooking like a big boy, holler! Below is the “recipe”, for this pan roasted venison (doe) back strap that I cooked a couple nights ago.
- the day before you want to cook, trim your backstrap of all silver skin and “marinate” in avocado oil, black pepper, dried minced garlic, and dried oregano. This marinade is not for the purpose of tenderizing or masking
-1 hour before you cook remove the backstrap from the marinade, and allow it to come to room temp on a plate
-5 minutes before cooking season with good salt 
-sear in skillet with beef tallow or other quality fat
-once seared on all sides, add butter, garlic and rosemary.
-continue to cook backstrap in butter rolling and basting constantly 
-remove from the ban when backstrap reaches 130-135 degrees 
-allow to rest for 10 minutes 
-slice and it should look like this
